  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong global consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is the process of making illegally gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three steps: placement, layering, and integration. This practice is widely recognized as a serious crime because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities while undermining the integrity of financial systems.\n\nVirtually all countries have laws and regulations in place to combat money laundering. These laws are often part of broader anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks, which include requirements for financial institutions and other entities to report suspicious activities, conduct customer due diligence, and maintain records.\n\nInternational cooperation has also been established to combat money laundering. Organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for AML and work to ensure that countries implement effective measures to prevent and detect money laundering activities. Additionally, various international treaties and conventions, such as the United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances and the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime, include provisions against money laundering.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity, and there is a robust legal and regulatory framework in place worldwide to combat it.",
